  We know by <fr:link
href="axt-005Q.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-005Q">axt-005Q</fr:link> that the <fr:link
href="axt-0030.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-0030">specialization preorder</fr:link> of the
  <fr:link
href="axt-003U.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-003U">Alexandroff topology</fr:link> always coincides with the order <fr:tex>\le</fr:tex>.
  Furthermore, we know by <fr:link
href="axt-005R.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-005R">axt-005R</fr:link> that it is finer than any topology
  whose specialization preorder coincides with the order <fr:tex>\le</fr:tex>.
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:p>
  The <fr:link
href="axt-004L.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-004L">upper topology</fr:link> is, in a sense, the dual of the Alexandroff
  topology: it is the <fr:em>coarsest possible topology</fr:em> whose specialization
  preorder coincides with the order <fr:tex>\le</fr:tex>.
</fr:p><fr:tree
